commit_message:
Fix rfc.sh's check for the project

From 'git remote show origin' we get 'openstack/nova.git' but gerrit's
ls-projects returns 'openstack/nova'

Change-Id: I4ea6361633d0e94895dbbdaf3837f12c6c307bfc

Fix outstanding pep8 errors for a clean trunk.

Also, add an option to run_tests.sh to skip running pep8. We have a separate
job in Jenkins which runs pep8, so there's no need to spin our wheels on it
during the test run.

Change-Id: I552330994e55a36fa96b63658493ed30e2720c85

commit_message:
POST /tokens: A chronicle of missing features

- Wrote new functional test for unscoped -> scoped token flow
- Revised /tokens samples & XSD
- Updated functional tests
- Added user & roles to POST /tokens
- Also fixed GET /tenants; was returning mixed up attributes
- Added support for POST /tokens w/ an unscoped tokenId w/o credentials
  - Revised credentials.xsd
  - Revised to accept scoped tokens... temporarily
- Removed the default tenant from the sampledata 'admin' user
- Added functional tests asserting behavior of Admins scoping to tenant
  - Keystone Admins should NOT (normally) be able to scope to a tenant,
    unless they have some *other* established role on that tenant.

Change-Id: I1a4bd52978e21a9f806e83ab1d431442ee49f633

bazillion times.

'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2011-09-17 15:23:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi I'm approving but I'd like more discussions about how the extensions are going to be output. One idea is to publish the extensions using xi:include statements to gather them all into one book for publishing on the docs.openstack.org site. This approach likely won't work well for the Identity API. So, another idea is to publish each extension as a separate one-pager (David Cramer calls this a "monolithic HTML" output). Your pom file does not produce the "monolithic HTML" output but I'd like to do so if separate deliverables is your preference. In other words, I prefer a particular HTML output for the extensions over the PDF you're currently outputting. Are you okay with that? I can create a pom that'll do what I'm hoping for display on the docs.openstack.org site.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2011-09-19 15:13:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Fixes LP Bug#755916 - Location field shows creds

Removes the Location field from the return of the
API server's GET /images/detail and GET /images/<ID>
calls. The Registry server API was unchanged, as the API
server needs to call the Registry server in order to
find location information...

Change-Id: I914456ad3879f19fa0b55c8a89b8217c193193d8

API server's GET /images/detail and GET /images/<ID>
calls. The Registry server API was unchanged, as the API
server needs to call the Registry server in order to
find location information...

commit_message:
Backend-managed role & service ID's (bug #834683)

- Revised SqlAlchemy Role & Service models
- Revised LDAP-backend 'id'/'name' attribute mgmt
  - Only persisting ID's
  - Returning id as both 'name' and 'id'
- Updated keystone.manage to CRUD by role/service name
- Revised backends.*ADMIN_ROLE* variables
- Updated json/xml encoding/decoding for roles & services
- Performing KEYSTONE_[SERVICE_]_ADMIN_ID lookups on first auth
  - This could be improved!
- Revised role & service samples & XSD's

Change-Id: I1aee372fb28d429f5e5410d43b7e2c6aa297d998

commit_message:
Fixes LP Bug #833285

Large objects, uploaded to Swift using the large object
manifest method, are uploaded in chunks/segments in the
Swift store driver.

Unfortunately, doing a DELETE on the object only deletes
the manifest, leaving the chunks/segments orphaned. This
patch makes the Swift store driver check for the existence
of an object manifest, and if found, deletes all intermediate
chunks, then deletes the object manifest itself.

Adds a functional test to check the segments are actually
deleted.

Change-Id: Ib5787581a57e419393faca198d867db757fc03b3

commit_message:
Fixes LP Bug #804429

The try: finally: block which called conn.close() in the
http store driver was flawed and the connection was not
being properly released. This changes the
http_response_iterator generator to accept the HTTP connection
and close it on final yield.

Change-Id: I545a7f5c93ccd196a99b50e8464778e075b549d8

commit_message:
Fixes Bug #851216

Fixes a recurring issue with tests that were
decorated with the @runs_sql decorator where the
file-based SQLite registry database used in those
tests was not being properly cleaned up, which was causing
some random-looking failures when python setup.py test was
run for the DEB builders on Jenkins.

According to Monty, files needed in testing do indeed need
to be in MANIFEST.in, so I added the test_migrations.conf
file to that. Sorry, BrianW!

Change-Id: I6535b999921d159de5d957f6b70df3c13310e449

commit_message:
Fixes Bug #851216

Fixes a recurring issue with tests that were
decorated with the @runs_sql decorator where the
file-based SQLite registry database used in those
tests was not being properly cleaned up, which was causing
some random-looking failures when python setup.py test was
run for the DEB builders on Jenkins.

According to Monty, files needed in testing do indeed need
to be in MANIFEST.in, so I added the test_migrations.conf
file to that. Sorry, BrianW!

Change-Id: I6535b999921d159de5d957f6b70df3c13310e449

commit_message:
the "glance index" provides a more style of listing images.
    1. the number of image indexes is "adapted" to the size of the console,
       while users still can customize the number of output per page through
       the parameter --limit
    2. users "need not" to press the "enter key" to confirm YES or NO.
    3. seamless output, you will never see the prompt message by scrolling the conso

    Change-Id: I8c9ba814b67e14d1fd4f0b90ce7e41d5202811a4
    usage: glance index (for adaptive listing)
            glance index --limit 15 (for customized listing)

Change-Id: I799dc31934d59043cda1fddd8df3b656c4c1e9a8

commit_message:
Added backend-managed primary key to User and Tenant model

- Revised functional tests to expect auto-generated id
- Revised manage.py to create users by name instead of id
- Functional tests passing with User.id & User.name
- Added User.id to Validate token response XSD/samples/python
- Restored full scope of test discovery
- Completely rewrote unit.test_users.py, because it needed some TLC
  - Added assertStatusCode to unit.test_users and refactored
  - Added assertContentType to unit.test_users and refactored
  - Abstracted out TestUpdateConflict
- Coercing JSON responses to UTF-8, per charset
- Added auto-generated PK to Tenant SQL model
- Updated management API to add, list and disable tenants by name
- Added get_by_name() to backend Tenant API
- Implemented Tenant.get_by_name() for SQL
- Simplified many of the "unit" tests further
- Abstracted keystone resources and their REST verbs away from the keystone test client
- Writing keystone client api for functional tests
  - Similar to the API "shortcuts" from the "unit" tests
- Finished common FunctionalTestCase
- Moved 'unit' tests over to the test.functional module... and rewrote them all
- Cleaned up unnecessary debug output
- Added pylint to pip-requires
- Removed alterdb

Change-Id: I45e689807166fc4f1cb59e385d2c7e680b36449d

Sure. I'll take a look into the nova XenServer plugin changes now.

One more comment regarding this changeset in Glance:

Could we add a simple option to select a different glance service catalog entry? I think what you have done in defaulting the serviceCatalog to 'glance' is great but it might also be worth adding a simple option so that if there are multiple glance entries in the service catalog then you can choose which one to use."}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2011-09-02 15:34:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Dan: I like the idea.  We should probably have options for both the service name (defaults to glance), and selecting the region (defaults to the 1st one).

Given that this patch was just to get the basic mechanics in place, would you mind if we added that functionality as a separate follow-on patch, just after this merges?'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2011-09-10 18:07:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Okay. I'm good with this now.

We'll need the nova branch here:

lp:~rackspace-titan/nova/glance-client-keystone

Additionally we need to add httplib2 as a glance runtime package dependency:

lp:~dan-prince/glance/ubuntu-glance-httplib2

Using all three of these modified branches I'm able to boot instances, create snapshots, etc with both libvirt and XenServer."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-09-12 14:23:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Looks good to me, approved

Various documentation-related changes.

Preparing wadl for wadl2docbook processing by adding in content from the doc and related markup.
Adding code samples to be used in documentation.
Merging in some changes that Yogi has made but which have not yet been approved.
Updating paths to samples to be ../common/samples

subject: Fix cached-images API endpoint
messages:
[{'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-31 03:47:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-31 03:49:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-31 04:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Sorry.. did not catch that earlier..'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-31 11:50:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't understand why the name of the variable is mandated by routes."}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-31 13:00:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The mapper.resource call uses the keyword 'id' by default. So for a url like /images/12, routes will parse that into a dictionary like {'id': 12}. We then pass that into our controller method like so: delete(self, id=id). Even though 'id' isn't defined as a keyword argument, we still pass it in as if it were. Changing 'id' to 'image_id' breaks this because we are still going to get 'id' back from routes."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-31 15:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

How on Earth did all the functional and unit tests pass, then, if that is the case? :('}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-31 15:22:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

There are no functional tests for the cache, and the unit tests are quite lacking.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-31 15:29:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, approved

commit_message:
Fix cached-images API endpoint

The recent chages that renamed 'id' to 'image_id' in the cached_images controller broke the API. This reverts a couple
of those changes.

Change-Id: I83345f87c7e5f1e35ef6646cb360819d489ec256

subject: Bug fix lp:726864
messages:
[{'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-31 02:21:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved

Simply horrible code. I don't know why anyone would ever think of submitting it.

Awesome."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2011-08-31 02:21:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build Started https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/glance-merge/41/ (1/3)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2011-08-31 02:21:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build Started https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/glance-pep8/212/ (3/3)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2011-08-31 02:22:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified

Build Successful 
 
https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/glance/89207/ : SUCCESS 
https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/glance-merge/41/ : SUCCESS 
https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/glance-pep8/212/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2011-08-31 02:22:47.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-31 03:53:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The routes library gives us the image id from the uri in a dictionary, where 'id' is the key. In wsgi.Resource, we unpack that dictionary directly into the controller method we want to call. This is unfortunate, but it forces us to have to use 'id' as the argument name in all of our controllers. There are two changes in this patch set that break this in cached_images.py, probably because we don't have proper test coverage. Here's the merge prop to get the image cache purge (delete) and prefetch (update) working again: https://review.openstack.org/#change,368"}]

revisions:
[{'created': '2011-08-25 20:08:10.000000000', 'message': 'Switch file based logging to WatchedFileHandler for logrotate

Fixes lp:772397

FileHandler opens the logfile at startup, keeps the stream open and
continues to log to it forever.

If logrotate decides to rotate the file, it will rename the original
file and a new file is created with the same attributes as the original
file.

The problem is that the process is still writing to the original file,
not the newly created file. Traditionally, system daemons respond to
a SIGHUP by re-opening log files and logrotate can be configured to
deliver this signal on rotation.

However, python has an elegant solution. WatchedFileHandler monitors
the inode for the specified log file name and, if that ever changes,
it re-opens the stream.

Nova already uses WatchedFileHandler to good effect. See:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/logrotate/+merge/50292

Change-Id: I7f693f133d230d65d7c94ebf3a2ec0c8b362f993
'}]
commit_message:
Switch file based logging to WatchedFileHandler for logrotate

Fixes lp:772397

FileHandler opens the logfile at startup, keeps the stream open and
continues to log to it forever.

If logrotate decides to rotate the file, it will rename the original
file and a new file is created with the same attributes as the original
file.

The problem is that the process is still writing to the original file,
not the newly created file. Traditionally, system daemons respond to
a SIGHUP by re-opening log files and logrotate can be configured to
deliver this signal on rotation.

However, python has an elegant solution. WatchedFileHandler monitors
the inode for the specified log file name and, if that ever changes,
it re-opens the stream.

Nova already uses WatchedFileHandler to good effect. See:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/logrotate/+merge/50292

Change-Id: I7f693f133d230d65d7c94ebf3a2ec0c8b362f993

[{'created': '2011-08-25 18:40:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fail 5G upload

Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fails to
upload image files greater than 5GB. The swift
store driver was not using the large object
manifest methods required to upload objects
greater than 5GB into Swift.

Adds configuration options to specify the
size in MB that an image file should be considered
for large object manifest, and a configurable
chunk size. We use a disk buffer of this size,
adding chunks of the image file into Swift and
then after all chunks are saved, add the manifest
to Swift.

Change-Id: I4b4421aa1bba584ab242016a041e864ef19d0214
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fail 5G upload

Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fails to
upload image files greater than 5GB. The swift
store driver was not using the large object
manifest methods required to upload objects
greater than 5GB into Swift.

Adds configuration options to specify the
size in MB that an image file should be considered
for large object manifest, and a configurable
chunk size. We use a disk buffer of this size,
adding chunks of the image file into Swift and
then after all chunks are saved, add the manifest
to Swift.

Change-Id: I4b4421aa1bba584ab242016a041e864ef19d0214

revisions:
[{'created': '2011-08-25 13:05:09.000000000', 'message': 'Switch file based logging to WatchedFileHandler for logrotate

Fixes lp:772397

FileHandler opens the logfile at startup, keeps the stream open and
continues to log to it forever.

If logrotate decides to rotate the file, it will rename the original
file and a new file is created with the same attributes as the original
file.

The problem is that the process is still writing to the original file,
not the newly created file. Traditionally, system daemons respond to
a SIGHUP by re-opening log files and logrotate can be configured to
deliver this signal on rotation.

However, python has an elegant solution. WatchedFileHandler monitors
the inode for the specified log file name and, if that ever changes,
it re-opens the stream.

Nova already uses WatchedFileHandler to good effect. See:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/logrotate/+merge/50292

Change-Id: I7f693f133d230d65d7c94ebf3a2ec0c8b362f993
'}]
commit_message:
Switch file based logging to WatchedFileHandler for logrotate

Fixes lp:772397

FileHandler opens the logfile at startup, keeps the stream open and
continues to log to it forever.

If logrotate decides to rotate the file, it will rename the original
file and a new file is created with the same attributes as the original
file.

The problem is that the process is still writing to the original file,
not the newly created file. Traditionally, system daemons respond to
a SIGHUP by re-opening log files and logrotate can be configured to
deliver this signal on rotation.

However, python has an elegant solution. WatchedFileHandler monitors
the inode for the specified log file name and, if that ever changes,
it re-opens the stream.

Nova already uses WatchedFileHandler to good effect. See:

  https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/logrotate/+merge/50292

Change-Id: I7f693f133d230d65d7c94ebf3a2ec0c8b362f993

commit_message:
Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fail 5G upload

Fixes LP Bug #827660 - Swift driver fails to
upload image files greater than 5GB. The swift
store driver was not using the large object
manifest methods required to upload objects
greater than 5GB into Swift.

Adds configuration options to specify the
size in MB that an image file should be considered
for large object manifest, and a configurable
chunk size. We use a disk buffer of this size,
adding chunks of the image file into Swift and
then after all chunks are saved, add the manifest
to Swift.

Change-Id: I4b4421aa1bba584ab242016a041e864ef19d0214

subject: Addresses glance/+spec/i18n
messages:
[{'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-19 03:25:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-19 15:00:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this

(11 inline comments)

Hey there, Justin! 

I started going through the code and noticed in many places you moved a positional format token (%s) to a keyword token (%(variable_name)s). This is fine to do, but really only necessary when there are multiple replacements in a single string. Anyways, if you want to keep with that pattern, you need to make sure you add '% locals()' onto the end of the string (there are several places where it is missing). 

There are also a few places where you call a function from within the keyword token (%(len(some_list))s), which I would like to avoid. Can you please do that above the format string and assign to a local variable which you can then reference from within the format string?

I only went through a couple of files from this branch, so make sure you look over the rest to address these issues.

Thanks for taking over this effort!"}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-19 18:50:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-19 18:52:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Cleaned up come issues with python2.6.

While working on packaging, we've discovered that the unittests do not work
on python2.6/Ubuntu Maverick. The first change to
keystone/common/template.py fixes an exception misuse. The rest are all
being explicit about using unittest2, because on 2.6 in some cases if you
just import unittest, you get left with an old API.

Change-Id: I783ef1cc14860578f8f61ae23e1afe8ac8f293a7

commit_message:
Made all sample data loading in one script.

Both keystone-manage and sampledata.sh logic moved to keystone package, kept
simple starter scripts in bin/ dir.
New sampledata module can theoretically be suitable for loading different
fixtures in one Python interpreter.
Snuck in a couple of extensions changes while fixing PEP8

Change-Id: Ie05a9afb528d41b93e56f41d252363b6de2d600d

Will do.

As for who Pattie Black is...

A frog enters a bank and hops over to a loan officer's desk.  "Hi," he says.  "I'd like to take out a loan."

The loan officer, Pattie Black, says, "Sure, I'd love to help.  Do you have any collateral?"

The frog hands over a small sculpture of a unicorn.

"I'll have to check with my manager," Pattie says.

She goes to her manager and explains the situation, then asks her manager, "What should I do?"

The manager replies, "It's a knick-knack, Pattie Black; give the frog a loan!"'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2011-08-12 19:07:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-12 20:49:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this

(14 inline comments)

Hi Kevin,

Great work in general. There are some things to fix up, noted in inline comments.

The big question, though, that I had with this patch (and the keystone integration support in general) is that I think there is some confusion as to the role that a tenant plays vs. a user. I think the two distinct concepts are kind of used for the same purpose in this code, and I think that's going to be a problem...

The tenant is basically the account that a user that has logged in belongs to. In Nova, the tenant is the *project*, which means that when Nova shares an image with another user, it will be providing the project as the tenant. However, the concept of sharing an image has to do with ownership of the image, and ownership is the purview of the *user*, not the tenant (project).

So those places in the documentation on shared images where you refer to a tenant you should really be referring to a user (the authenticated user).

Does this makes sense?

Also, Brian Waldon mentioned that he would prefer this:

GET /members/<MEMBER ID>/shared-images

to be just:

GET /shared-images/<MEMBER_ID>

What are your thoughts on that? I think I'd actually prefer GET /shared-images/<MEMBER_ID> because the /members resource is technically the purview of Keystone...

Thanks!
jay"}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2011-08-12 21:05:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

For clarity, I never (intentionally) refer to the _user_ in the context; the context just stores it.  I'm doing all the ownership and authorization computation/decisions based on the tenant, and yes I'm aware that maps to the project.  My thought here is that images belong to the tenant (think backup), and can be shared with other tenants (company 'foo' sells ready-made images to company 'bar').  Given this, what I've stated in the documentation hunks is correct :)

I have no problem with using 'GET /shared-images/<MEMBER ID>'; that makes plenty of sense.

Will follow-up soon with replies to your in-line comments (not sure how you managed to get it all into a single response!)"}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2011-08-12 21:19:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (7 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 1132, 'date': '2011-08-12 21:38:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

(Just to be clear, I have not attempted to address the switchable owner stuff that jaypipes and I discussed on the IRC channel; I felt that belonged in a separate commit, and I'll generate one just as soon as this gets merged in.  (Trying to avoid conflicts in glance.common.context...))"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-14 20:19:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this

Hi Kevin,

I would prefer that the things we addressed on IRC would be done in this changeset. Also, I'd like to see the functional tests done in this changeset, too. The functional tests are really the big system tests and even though you've added some unit tests, I'd still like to see the functional ones completed before I feel comfortable adding this functionality to trunk. Let me know if you'd like assistance creating the functional tests.

lgtm.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2011-08-10 02:23:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not submit

Hi Justin,

Something you've done in this branch is causing python-glance to install run_tests.py to /usr/share/pyshared/run_tests.py.

Any idea what that would be.

Anyway I'd like to see this fixed before you merge because this will break using Glance w/ Nova which currently requires python-glance and also suffers from this same bug.

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/823676"}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-10 03:57:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Dan,

I have a couple of questions.

1. I am not an expert on the packaging of glance/nova, but the problem you listed seems to be an issue with packaging not this branch. Do you agree?

2. As far as I can tell, nothing in this merge-prop would be responsible for installing run_tests.py to the mentioned location (as shown by the bug in python-nova)

3. My understanding would be that any merge-prop from glance with the same parent would cause the problem

Thanks,
Justin Shepherd'}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-10 04:28:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

So i created an egg from this merge-prop:

# python setup.py bdist_egg

And looking at the egg contents once it was unzipped, I can not find any references to "run_tests.py".

$ ls
EGG-INFO                glance                  glance-2011.3-py2.6.egg
$ ls glance | grep -i run_tests.py
$ ls EGG-INFO/ | grep -i run_tests.py
$ 

----------

Dan, how did you determine that this merge-prop is putting run_tests.py in /usr/share/pyshared/?

Thanks,
Justin'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2011-08-10 11:50:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

run_tests.py is unrelated:

https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/dont-install-run_tests.py/+merge/71007'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2011-08-10 11:56:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Justin,

I think when you copied the DistUtilsExtra.auto code over from nova's setup.py you inherited the same problem it had.

Check out Soren's branch that appears to resolve the issue for nova:

https://code.launchpad.net/~soren/nova/dont-install-run_tests.py/+merge/71007

Hope this helps."}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-10 14:11:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1032, 'date': '2011-08-10 14:12:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Addresses glance/+spec/i18n

Added gettext.install to glance endpoints, setup.py, and run_tests.py. Wrapped all exceptions in common/exception.py with gettext.

Included fix for bug lp:823676.

Change-Id: Ied4381e1676227afea857acd01f4754e6a181106

commit_message:
Adds support for authenticating via ec2 signatures

* modifies credentials to store tenant id
* adds credentials backend api
* cleans up a bunch of whitespace errors
* adds new /ec2token endpoint for new logic
* fixes unit/base.py test case
* adds unittests for ec2_authn
* includes compatibility for clients that ignore ports

Change-Id: I1bd1e549cc74cbb708059b07b2928bf09c8ba1ca

commit_message:
Addresses Bug lp:781410

Currently API throws a 500 error if it attempts to return an image
that has been removed from the filesystem but still lives in the DB.
Fixes it so the API now throws a 404 error when this happens.

Change-Id: I8fcf53de7760d462b5f938c71cb29ee837d172af

commit_message:
Add @skip_if_disabled decorator to test.utils and integrate
it into the base functional API test case. The S3 functional
test case now uses test_api.TestApi as its base class and
the setUp() method sets the disabled and disabled_message
attributes that the @skip_if_disabled decorator uses.

The S3 test case now tests all the methods that are tested
for the filesystem store driver in test_api.TestApi

Removed the test.functional.test_s3.conf file as it was no
longer needed.

Change-Id: I308d7a655c8c26339d0e2560634421935bbc8b5d

[{'created': '2011-08-04 17:48:30.000000000', 'message': 'Gets Keystone a bit more inline with the way that
other OpenStack projects run tests. Basically, adds the standard
run_tests.sh script, modifies the run_tests.py script to do the
following:

a) Correctly create a test configuration file that is passed
   to keystone-manage and keystone. This allows you to test
   keystone on a server that already has keystone running on it
b) Some DRY cleanup around the removal of database files that
   get created in the course of testing
c) Creates a virtualenv automatically with the -V (-f) flag,
   which reads the tools/pip-requires file and constructs a virtualenv
   with all dependencies installed

commit_message:
Gets Keystone a bit more inline with the way that
other OpenStack projects run tests. Basically, adds the standard
run_tests.sh script, modifies the run_tests.py script to do the
following:

a) Correctly create a test configuration file that is passed
   to keystone-manage and keystone. This allows you to test
   keystone on a server that already has keystone running on it
b) Some DRY cleanup around the removal of database files that
   get created in the course of testing
c) Creates a virtualenv automatically with the -V (-f) flag,
   which reads the tools/pip-requires file and constructs a virtualenv
   with all dependencies installed

Change-Id: I8defa5956a7f23258936d04a11655d36a71226ec

Additional MIME types are normalized down to 'application/xml'
and 'application/json' to minimize impact on underlying layers.

encoding) to the wsgi environment for underlying apps to
optionally utilize. (note: the legacy layer now looks for the
KEYSTONE_API_VERSION).

commit_message:
Added automatic test discovery to unit tests  and removed all dead tests.

- Removing unused functional test suite
- Revised normalizing filter tests
- Fix for all tests cases in unit.test_server
- Removing unused test class with ambiguous inheritence
- Migrated broken unit tests to system test
- Migrated tests to system tests
- Replaced test_keystone.py with automatic test discovery
- Renamed test/system to test/functional
- Removed proprietary run_tests.py which is now redundant/deprecated
- Removed bootstrap.sh, as it was only used by system tests.

Change-Id: Ied6865f611275a2408a5d1458a9edd7d0375ffa0

commit_message:
Implemented @utils.skip_test, @utils.skip_unless and @utils.skip_if functionality in glance/test/utils.py. Added glance/tests/unit/test_skip_examples.py which contains example skip case usages.

Fixed issue where ./run_tests.sh would not execute pep8. Fixed couple of pep8 violations in test_skip_examples.py

commit_message:
Gets Keystone a bit more inline with the way that
other OpenStack projects run tests. Basically, adds the standard
run_tests.sh script, modifies the run_tests.py script to do the
following:

a) Correctly create a test configuration file that is passed
   to keystone-manage and keystone. This allows you to test
   keystone on a server that already has keystone running on it
b) Some DRY cleanup around the removal of database files that
   get created in the course of testing
c) Creates a virtualenv automatically with the -V (-f) flag,
   which reads the tools/pip-requires file and constructs a virtualenv
   with all dependencies installed

Change-Id: I90bc888a17e2e0041245095c586598ab86db58aa

commit_message:
Added support for versioned openstack MIME types

Additional MIME types are normalized down to 'application/xml'
and 'application/json' to minimize impact on underlying layers.
Also added normalized KEYSTONE_API_VERSION and
KEYSTONE_RESPONSE_ENCODING (simplified prefferred Accept
encoding) to the wsgi environment for underlying apps to
optionally utilize. (note: the legacy layer now looks for the
KEYSTONE_API_VERSION).

Includes additional pylint fixes.

Change-Id: I06b82e603799ed89a2e2d92005892ede0a295225

commit_message:
Added support for versioned openstack MIME types

Additional MIME types are normalized down to 'application/xml' and 'application/json' to minimize impact on underlying layers. Also added normalized KEYSTONE_API_VERSION and KEYSTONE_RESPONSE_ENCODING (simplified prefferred Accept encoding) to the wsgi environment for underlying apps to optionally utilize. (note: the legacy layer now looks for the KEYSTONE_API_VERSION).

Change-Id: I654cca34e3d01b134f6fedf9114e11a0a98a2740
